title: For Sale:  WINCHESTER 1886 Rifle
postcontent: This is a fair old 1886 in .40-65 WCF, made in 1887 (serial #5851), the second year of production. It has a round 26” barrel and shotgun butt stock. The bore is somewhat rough but shootable with visible rifling and even, shallow pitting from black powder. The case colored receiver is lightly and evenly pitted from rust, with no case color remaining. The barrel and magazine are evenly rusted overall with some slight blue remaining visible. The action is tight. The lower tang shows a lot of blue, and may be refinished or came on another gun. I would speculate that the butt stock is a replacement as well as the magazine retaining band - also probably several screws. But all metal appears to be original Winchester, whether or not it was all born together. The good news is it old enough to be an antique, so no FFL is needed to ship. No letter or box accompanies the gun. That's all I can tell!

title: For Sale:  Savage 10 FCP-SR Digital Camo.
postcontent: This is a hard to find Savage 10 FCP-SR in digital camo (the Savage Manufacturer part number is 19480).  It's chambered in .308/7.62 NATO.  This isn't the new model FCP-SR that's on every shelf in every box store.  Guys who shoot long range know this is a vastly superior build compared to the new model.  I configured this rifle for a long range class I took in Virginia that was taught by Dan Newbury. The rifle features a 24 inch heavy fluted barrel with a muzzle break, a one piece picitinny rail, digital camo AccuStock, AccuTrigger, and an all steel construction 10 round detachable box magazine by Accurate Mag Company.  In addition to that, I have a 6-18 Vortex Crossfire II scope with a level attached, a cheek riser, and an imitation Harris bipod.  I zeroed the rifle at a hundred yards last August, cleaned it, oiled it, and put it away.  The only adjustment I never made to it is on the magazine feed lip.  I never bothered to buy the adjustment tool because I feed the ammo by hand one round at a time when I shoot long range.  The mag feed lip probably needs to be opened up about 3 thousandths or so to get the cartridges to feed more smoothly.  The adjustment tool costs about 25 bucks.If you have any questions, feel free to ask.  If the ad is up, the rifle is still for sale.  1000 dollars gets everything I listed in the ad.  900 gets you everything but the optic.  Not looking for trades at this time.  Be sure to check out my ad for an unfired AK47 Arsenal SAM7 UF.  Thanks for your interest.
